<h2><a name='sect0' href='#toc0'>Name</a></h2>

<p> shmem_addr_accessible - Indicates if an address is accessible via
OpenSHMEM operations from the specified remote PE.
<h2><a name='sect1' href='#toc1'>Synopsis</a></h2>

<p> C or C++: <br>
<pre>#include &lt;mpp/shmem.h&gt;
int shmem_addr_accessible(const void *addr, int pe);
</pre> Fortran: <br>
<pre>INCLUDE "mpp/shmem.fh"
LOGICAL LOG, SHMEM_ADDR_ACCESSIBLE
INTEGER pe
LOG = SHMEM_ADDR_ACCESSIBLE(addr, pe)
</pre>
<h2><a name='sect2' href='#toc2'>Description</a></h2>

<p> shmem_addr_accessible is a query function that indicates whether
a local address is accessible via SHMEM operations from the specified remote
PE. <p>
This function verifies that the remote PE is accessible via SHMEM data
transfer functions from the local PE, and that the specified address is
in a symmetric data segment with respect to the remote PE. <p>

<h2><a name='sect3' href='#toc3'>Return Values</a></h2>

<p>
C: The return value is 1 if addr is a symmetric data object and accessible
via SHMEM operations from the specified remote PE; otherwise, it is 0. <p>
Fortran:
The return value is .TRUE. if addr is a symmetric data object and accessible
via SHMEM operations from the specified remote PE; otherwise, it is .FALSE..
<p>

